@node "Introduction" ""

 The purpose of this program is to randomly change some system
 preferences every time your computer reboots. This is achieved
 by  copying different files over the saved pref files. A degree
 of control  is provided by the configuration file.

 This program is a direct outgrowth of my old PicRnd program.
 That program worked only on workbench pattern files stored in
 the Sys:Prefs/Patterns drawer. Some people commented that they
 wanted to use full screen graphics for workbench back drops,
 and smaller repeating graphics for window backdrops. So I
 added a Config File that will let the user specify different
 directories and different file names. Now you can have a
 workbench pattern  drawer, a window pattern drawer, a pointer
 pref drawer, a sound pref drawer, etc.
 
 This program was written in C, and compiled using version 5 of
 the Lattice C compiler. The test bed was an Amiga 3000 running
 Workbench 3.1.

@endnode

@node "Installation" ""

 To install this program do the following:

 1) Unarchive to a temporary storage space.

 2) Copy SysRnd to some place in your command path (like Sys:c).

 3) Copy SysRnd.cfg to your Sys:s directory. If this file is not
    present, the program will not run.

 4) Add the command SysRnd to your Startup-Sequence some  place
    before the IPrefs command.

 5) Modify SysRnd.cfg to your requirements (see configuration
    section).
    
 6) Change your saved preference settings to the ones specified
    in the SysRnd.cfg file.

 7) Reboot your computer.

That's about all there is to it. You should be up and running.

@endnode

@node "HowItWorks" ""

 When the program runs, it will read the SysRnd.cfg file. For each
 line it will:

 1) go to the directory specified. 

 2) Delete any of the named files, if they exist, in that directory.

 3) Randomly clone files in that directory for each of the file names
    given in the SysRnd.cfg line.

 4) Process the next line, until the end of SysRnd.cfg is reached. 
 
 5) Change back to the directory that was active when the program
    was run.

 6) Exit the program.
 
 Pretty simple stuff really.

@endnode

@node "ConfigFile" ""

 SysRnd.cfg must reside in your Sys:s directory for SysRnd to find
 it. The file must be in ASCII text format only. Each line must be
 of the  following format:

 Complete Directory path Entry, Save File 1, Save File 2, etc.....

 For example:

 Sys:Prefs/Patterns,WBPic,WDPic
 
 Some restrictions on SysRnd.cfg are:

 1) No line can be longer than 80 characters.

 2) There can be no more than 15 lines.

 3) The file must end with a blank new line.
 
 4) There can be no spaces in the SysRnd.cfg file.
 
 Examine the sample SysRnd.cfg file. It causes the program to:
 
 1) Look for the directory Sys:Prefs/Patterns.
 
 2) It then deletes WBPic and WDPic if they exist. 
 
 3) It reads the Sys:Prefs/Patterns directory and randomly
    clones two files to WBPic and WDPic.
    
 If your WBPattern prefs are set to these files, they will be used
 when IPrefs runs.

@endnode

